  "prompt": "Which was first smart mobile in the world?",
  "response": "The IBM Simon, released in 1994, is widely considered the world's first smartphone. It was developed by IBM and BellSouth and featured several revolutionary capabilities for its time:\n\n1. Touchscreen interface\n2. Email capability\n3. Calendar and address book\n4. Calculator\n5. Ability to install third-party applications\n6. Could send and receive faxes\n\nWhile it was very expensive (around $1,100 at launch) and looked quite different from modern smartphones, the IBM Simon is generally recognized as the first device that combined mobile phone capabilities with personal digital assistant (PDA) features, essentially creating the first smartphone concept.\n\nHowever, some technology historians might argue about the precise definition of a \"smartphone.\" Devices like the Nokia 9000 Communicator (released in 1996) are also sometimes cited as early smartphone predecessors.\n\nThe modern smartphone era is typically considered to have begun with the introduction of the iPhone by Apple in 2007, which dramatically transformed the mobile phone industry and set new standards for smartphone design and functionality.",
